    clinicalRelevance: "Troponin is the gold standard for AMI diagnosis. A rise and/or fall pattern with at least one value above the 99th percentile URL is diagnostic in the appropriate clinical context. CK-MB relative index (CK-MB/total CK × 100) >5% suggests cardiac source. BNP >100 pg/mL or NT-proBNP >300 pg/mL supports heart failure diagnosis.",
    signsSymptoms: "AMI: chest pain, diaphoresis, dyspnea, nausea, jaw/arm pain. Heart failure: dyspnea, orthopnea, peripheral edema, fatigue, jugular venous distension.",
    assessment: "hs-cTnI/T: detectable within 1-3 hours of AMI onset, peaks 12-24 hours, remains elevated 7-14 days. Serial testing at 0 and 3 hours (or 0 and 1 hour with hs-cTn). CK-MB: rises 3-6 hours, peaks 12-24 hours, normal by 48-72 hours (useful for reinfarction detection). CK-MB index = (CK-MB/total CK) × 100; >5% = cardiac source. BNP/NT-proBNP: NT-proBNP has longer half-life, unaffected by nesiritide therapy, renally cleared (age/renal adjusted cutoffs needed).",
    management: "AMI: serial troponin measurements (0h, 3h or 0h, 1h rapid rule-out). Heart failure: BNP/NT-proBNP for diagnosis and monitoring treatment response. Point-of-care testing available for troponin and BNP.",
    complications: "Troponin elevation without AMI: myocarditis, PE, sepsis, renal failure, cardiac surgery, strenuous exercise. Falsely elevated troponin: heterophilic antibodies, macrotroponin. Falsely elevated BNP: obesity (falsely LOW), renal failure (falsely HIGH).",
    clinicalPearls: ["hs-cTn is the PREFERRED biomarker for AMI diagnosis—has replaced CK-MB as primary marker", "CK-MB returns to baseline in 48-72 hours, making it useful for detecting REINFARCTION (troponin remains elevated too long)", "BNP is falsely LOW in obesity and falsely HIGH in renal failure—know these interferences"],
    examPitfalls: ["Troponin elevation is NOT specific for AMI—many non-ACS causes exist (myocarditis, PE, sepsis, renal failure)", "CK-MB index >5% suggests cardiac source; <5% suggests skeletal muscle (marathon runners, rhabdomyolysis)", "NT-proBNP requires age-adjusted cutoffs and is affected by renal function more than BNP"],
