    examPitfalls: ["SDS replaced MSDS—the format changed from 8 sections to 16 standardized sections under GHS", "Sodium azide in drain pipes forms explosive metal azides—always flush drains with large volumes of water when discarding azide-containing solutions", "Formalin is 37% formaldehyde in water—formaldehyde is the carcinogenic agent, formalin is the aqueous solution"],
    faqJson: [{ question: "What are the 16 sections of the SDS?", answer: "Key sections: (1) identification, (2) hazards, (3) composition, (4) first aid, (5) fire-fighting, (6) accidental release, (7) handling/storage, (8) exposure controls/PPE, (9) physical properties, (10) stability, (11) toxicology, (12) ecological, (13) disposal, (14) transport, (15) regulatory, (16) other. Sections 2, 4, and 8 are most critical for lab workers." }, { question: "What fire extinguisher type is used for flammable liquid fires?", answer: "Class B fire extinguisher is used for flammable liquid fires (solvents, oils, gasoline). Most clinical labs have ABC combination extinguishers. Class C is for electrical fires. NEVER use water on flammable liquid (Class B) or electrical (Class C) fires." }]
