    overview: "Candida species are the most common cause of fungal infections (candidiasis) in humans. C. albicans is the most prevalent species, but non-albicans species (C. glabrata, C. tropicalis, C. parapsilosis, C. krusei, C. auris) are increasing in frequency and often have reduced susceptibility to fluconazole. Candida exists as a commensal in the oral cavity, GI tract, and female genital tract, becoming pathogenic when normal host defenses are compromised.",
