    assessment: "Gram stain/KOH prep: budding yeast cells ± pseudohyphae/true hyphae. Germ tube test: C. albicans (and C. dubliniensis) produce germ tubes when incubated in serum at 35-37°C for 2-3 hours—definitive identification. Chlamydospore production on cornmeal-Tween 80 agar: C. albicans produces terminal chlamydospores. Chromogenic agar: species-specific color colonies (C. albicans = green, C. tropicalis = blue). MALDI-TOF MS: rapid, accurate identification of all Candida species. C. auris: frequently misidentified as C. haemulonii by conventional methods—MALDI-TOF or molecular methods required.",
    management: "Mucocutaneous: topical azoles (clotrimazole, nystatin), oral fluconazole for recurrent/severe. Invasive candidiasis: echinocandins (caspofungin, micafungin, anidulafungin) first-line for candidemia; fluconazole step-down if C. albicans and susceptible. C. krusei: intrinsically resistant to fluconazole. C. auris: often resistant to fluconazole, variably resistant to amphotericin B, usually susceptible to echinocandins.",
    complications: "Candidemia: 30-40% mortality. Disseminated candidiasis: endophthalmitis, hepatosplenic candidiasis, endocarditis. C. auris: multidrug resistance, nosocomial outbreaks, environmental persistence on surfaces, difficult decontamination.",
